<tr>
  <td><%= user.id %></td>
  <td><%= link_to user.name, user_path(user) %></td>
  <td>
    <%= form_for(user) do |f| %>
      <%= f.select(:role, User.roles.keys.map {|role| [role.titleize, role]}) %>
      <%= f.submit "Revise Role" %>
    <% end %>
  </td>
  <td>
    <%= link_to "Delete Account", user_path(user), method: :delete, data: { confirm: "This account will be permanently deleted. Do you want to proceed?" } %>
  </td>
</tr>

<!--Explanation of form allowing admin to change a user's role:
calling User.roles returns this hash:
{"unassigned_user"=>0, "patient"=>1, "therapist"=>2, "admin"=>3}
Then, calling User.roles.keys returns this array:
["unassigned_user", "patient", "therapist", "admin"]
And then, ["unassigned_user", "patient", "therapist", "admin"].map {|role| [role.titleize, role]}
will return:
[["Unassigned User", "unassigned_user"], ["Patient", "patient"], ["Therapist", "therapist"], ["Admin", "admin"]]
So in the dropdown menu, we'll have something like <option value="unassigned_user">Unassigned User</option>
-->
